Prompt: Meeting Intelligence Extraction

Role

Act as a Program Management Analyst and Technical Strategist responsible for extracting operational intelligence from meeting transcripts.

Your job is to convert a raw meeting transcript into structured program management outputs that can be used for project tracking, decision documentation, and leadership updates.

Assume the meeting may involve technical programs, government IT projects, security compliance, operational deployments, and cross-organizational coordination.

Focus on identifying what actually matters operationally.

⸻

Input

Below is a meeting transcript.

Analyze the transcript and extract the most important information, ignoring filler conversation.

Transcript:

[PASTE TRANSCRIPT HERE]


⸻

Output Structure

Provide the analysis in the following structured sections.

⸻

1. Executive Summary (BLUF)

Provide a 3-5 sentence summary explaining:
	•	What the meeting was about
	•	The most important outcomes
	•	Any critical risks or blockers

⸻

2. Key Decisions

List all decisions made during the meeting.

For each decision include:

Decision
Description
Decision Owner
Reason for Decision
Implications

⸻

3. Action Items

Extract all tasks or follow-ups mentioned in the meeting.

Format as a table:

| Task | Owner | Due Date | Priority | Dependencies | Notes |

If owner or due date are unclear, mark “TBD”.

⸻

4. Milestones or Deliverables

Identify any program milestones, deadlines, releases, or deliverables mentioned.

Format:

Milestone
Description
Target Date
Owner
Status

⸻

5. Risks or Issues

Identify any risks, blockers, or problems discussed.

Format:

Risk
Impact
Likelihood
Owner
Mitigation Strategy

Example risks:
	•	Security compliance gaps
	•	Funding uncertainty
	•	Vendor dependencies
	•	Integration problems

⸻

6. Key Topics Discussed

Provide a list of the major themes discussed during the meeting.

Example categories:
	•	Architecture decisions
	•	Security compliance
	•	Deployment planning
	•	Funding
	•	Vendor coordination
	•	Data governance

⸻

7. Important Facts or Data Points

Extract any critical facts, numbers, timelines, or references mentioned.

Example:
	•	Contract value
	•	Timeline milestones
	•	System architecture components
	•	Compliance requirements

⸻

8. Stakeholders Mentioned

List all organizations, teams, or roles mentioned in the meeting.

Example:

Stakeholder
Role in discussion

⸻

9. Follow-up Questions That Should Be Asked

Based on the discussion, identify important questions leadership or the program team should clarify.

Example categories:
	•	Governance
	•	Funding
	•	Security compliance
	•	Data ownership
	•	Integration dependencies

⸻

10. Strategic Observations

Provide insightful observations a program manager or CIO advisor should notice.

Examples:
	•	Misalignment between stakeholders
	•	Hidden risks
	•	Architectural concerns
	•	Policy gaps
	•	Program governance issues

⸻

11. Suggested Next Steps

Based on the transcript, recommend concrete next steps for the program team.

⸻

Follow-Up Prompt (Brainstorming Prompt)

After the extraction step, run this second prompt to generate strategic thinking.

⸻

Prompt: Strategic Program Advisor

Using the extracted meeting analysis above, act as:
	•	a federal enterprise architect
	•	a program governance advisor
	•	a technical strategy consultant

Provide additional insights that would help the program succeed.

Generate the following:

1. Strategic Risks Not Mentioned

Identify risks that were not discussed but likely exist.

⸻

2. Questions Leadership Should Ask

Generate questions a CIO, Deputy CIO, or Program Executive would likely ask.

⸻

3. Architecture Considerations

Identify technical architecture issues or design implications.

⸻

4. Policy or Compliance Implications

Highlight potential concerns involving:
	•	FedRAMP
	•	FISMA
	•	Privacy Act
	•	CJIS
	•	Data governance

⸻

5. Program Management Improvements

Suggest improvements to:
	•	governance
	•	coordination
	•	decision tracking
	•	documentation

⸻

6. Potential Opportunities

Identify opportunities for:
	•	automation
	•	integration
	•	analytics
	•	cost savings
	•	operational improvements

